column1: Who will win the 2019 Bolivian presidential election?
column6: ['Elections and Referenda']

Considering how Morales resigned, caving to the armed forces, and how the acting prez came to power this is now a problematic question and should be taken down or re-written to include the ongoing political developments including the politics of the "religous right" and the "mystery delay" ballot tabulation during October vote.

https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election/morales-shadow-looms-large-in-bolivia-as-clashes-test-new-leader-idUSKBN1XN1XC https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/11/morales-people-ready-return-pacify-bolivia-191113193229019.html https://apnews.com/494457977191419db3cea4ff4d157f96 https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RVLjte648N4
Per others, question needs to be either nullified (preferred) or go with Morales win as flawed as it was. Note that Morales resigned - but still “won”.

This question should either be nullified - since there will be no runoff - or resolved affirmative for Morales as of October 24, when the election panel formally announced that Morales was the first round winner.
The GJedi might suspend this Q now that Morales has hit the silk. My numbers are pure conjecture until I hear from some of my folks who actually know things.

Official results from the Oct. 20 elections gave Morales just enough of a majority needed to avoid a risky runoff against a united opposition. Second-place finisher Carlos Mesa says the count was manipulated and has refused to accept it. He wants a runoff in any case — noting the OAS itself suggested that as a way to ensure confidence in the system. https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/evo-morales-says-hed-welcome-election-audit-in-bolivia/2019/10/26/e88f0cc4-f864-11e9-b2d2-1f37c9d82dbb_story.html
Seems Morales isn't above ignoring the will of the people in order to represent the people. Willing to bet the same will happen in a run-off, assuming there is one.
If there isn't sufficient fraud to avoid a runoff now, it will be taken care of at that time.
https://www.euronews.com/2019/10/22/clashes-erupt-in-bolivia-as-morales-leads-contested-vote-count

Must be day for close election results. Sounding like a runoff will be required (Morales won but not by enough to preclude runoff) https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/21/bolivia-confusion-over-election-results-sparks-fear-and-protests
https://www.la-razon.com/suplementos/animal_politico/Encuesta-Evo-aleja-mesa-puntos-elecciones_0_3238476128.html

Because how long has he been in power he has been able to gain control of institutions that favor him on the next elections. In Latin America there's an overall trend of candidates from the left party to get into power and stay there. He supports Nicolas Maduro (who's doing the same thing) despite of having low popularity inside Bolivia. There is, however, a small chance that his external aid will decrease or even stop because of Venezuela's situation that is getting worse, and internally running out of resources to benefit key leaders that keep him in power, but this scenario seems like more long term.

From the Economist “Bolivians head to the polls on Sunday to elect the president and all members of parliament. The leftist incumbent, Evo Morales, is gunning for a fourth term on a platform of economic stability. Thanks to a commodities boom and redistributive policies, annual growth has averaged 5% since he first took office in 2006. The share of the population living on less than $1.90 a day has dropped by two-thirds. But Mr Morales’s popularity is threatened by public anger over his slow response to wildfires in the Bolivian Amazon and his defiance of the constitution and a national referendum vote to run again. The government is spending big bucks on propaganda and freebies—including ovens and tractors—to try to avert a run-off against Carlos Mesa, a former president, on December 15th. The threshold for winning outright in the first round is 40%, with a ten-point lead over the nearest rival. Polls suggest it will be close.“
Sounds like another autocrat has emerged... https://www.economist.com/node/21773208?frsc=dg%7Ce

This Article points out stability but at some cost (imperious nature, ignoring the courts). Regardless, likely Morales will win... https://www.npr.org/2019/10/14/767967304/how-bolivias-evo-morales-could-win-a-4th-term-as-president

Morales has won three times in the past and it looks like he's still the most popular. There will probably be a runoff but unless all voters who didn't vote for him can coalesce around the other candidate (which seems unlikely) he will probably win again. Though sentiment against him is growing.

Things getting tighter in Bolivia... https://www.reuters.com/article/us-bolivia-election-polls/bolivian-election-polls-show-opposition-reeling-in-president-morales-idUSKBN1WP355 https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/11/bolivia-president-feels-election-heat-amid-anger-wildfires-evo-morales

To win in first round Morales needs majority of votes or 40% and 10% lead. Majority is rather not possible and if he fails to win in first through 40/10 rule he still has huge chance as according to https://www.eldeber.com.bo/152929_la-estrategia-de-bajar-al-otro-no-rendiria-frutos-a-mesa-ni-a-ortiz-y-favoreceria-a-morales
I am heavily favoring Morales because he is the incumbent, and has won three straight elections. He also leads in polling, although not be enough to avoid a run-off.

I think Carlos Mesa is going to win the election because Evo Morales reputation has been tarnished because of recent accusations of corruption and mismanagement. There is also a lot of public anger towards him because he decided to run for a fourth term even though he lost a referendum on the issue in 2016.

I don't have a good reference class for this question. Morales is the incumbent, and there is risk of corruption working in his favor, especially with the concern about running for another term. However Mesa is also really well known. Perhaps the decision will be made by the departments with the large cities. In the cities, Morales has the absolute larger vote, because he has more votes overall, however, Mesa's supporters are generally urban. 65% of the population is urban: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bolivia#Demographics Everything I read suggests Morales has the rural areas sewn up, so it really depends on if the cities are more concerned about corruption and the threat to democracy of re-electing Morales, or other issues like the fires. Anneinak already posted this, but it influenced me, too. https://www.as-coa.org/articles/poll-tracker-bolivias-2019-presidential-race

Although the push for a fourth term may be viewed suspiciously as a few steps removed from dictatorship, Evo Morales has otherwise governed successfully. Furthermore, as an aborigine of Bolivia, his support will continue to run deep. Ergo, unless credible allegations of corruption and crime are tied to him or his campaign, the mantle of Bolivia's presidency is expected to remain his.
Morales backers will count the votes Do any recount of the votes And will remain President In Spanish accounting it is said "El quien cuenta y quien recuenta queda con la cuenta.
When you control the levers of government in a Latin American country, the odds are ever in your favor.

In order to become President of Bolivia one needs to "win 40% of votes with a 10-point lead over the runner-up", or 50% of the vote. The current polling that Morales will at least win the first round vote guaranteeing him a place in the December run off on the 15th December.
